 <dc:title>Universality of equilibrium one-dimensional transport from gauge
  invariance</dc:title>
 <dc:creator>Alekseev, Anton Yu.</dc:creator>
 <dc:creator>Cheianov, Vadim V.</dc:creator>
 <dc:creator>Froehlich, Jurg</dc:creator>
 <dc:subject>Condensed Matter - Mesoscopic Systems and Quantum Hall Effect</dc:subject>
 <dc:subject>High Energy Physics - Theory</dc:subject>
 <dc:description>  In this letter we address the question how interactions affect the DC
conductance of a one-dimensional electron system not necessarily adequately
described by the Luttinger model. Using a Laughlin type argument, we show that
gauge invariance protects the universal value of the conductance of $e^2/h$ per
channel per spin orientation if the system possesses two conserved charges
conjugate to the chemical potentials of the external reservoirs.
</dc:description>
